I am a firm believer in the simple formula for success (although it be easier said than done):

-Planning - (also called forethought) is the process of thinking about and organizing the activities required to achieve a desired goal.

-Commitment - A verbal or written obligation, pledge or promise to do something.

-Dedication/Determination - A continuous resolute movement towards some objective or end regardless of influence or obstacle.

-Initiative - Acting without hesitation to take the first step in a process that once taken determines subsequent events. Make Stuff Happen Rather Than Wait For It To Happen To You.....Work the Strategy (Plan) and do not be afraid to change the Tactic if it is warranted but always put effort in movement towards that goal daily and the goal will be laid at your feet.

No matter what your experience, no matter what your qualifications are, no matter who thinks you can or cannot do it.......these are merely outside influences which are personal limitations you choose to carry as a burden which makes you look to the ground or toss to the side so you can stand up straight and look towards your goal. People will call you unqualified, crazy, stupid or foolish because they are victims of their own self doubt......they are people who do not believe in themselves therefore they remind others of how they should not believe in themselves (misery loves company). Believe in yourself and work the formula to achieve your goal!

I started as a Special Effects at Weta Workshop more than 20 years ago and am now the Content Coordinator. I've had the chance to work on some amazing projects from "The Lord of the Rings Trilogy", "Avatar", District 9", "Elysium", "The Hobbit Trilogy" and "Warcraft". I've been fascinated by 3D Printing since Weta got its first printer in the late 2000s.

My late wife got me an Up Mini for my birthday at the end of 2014 (she was the best wife ever) and that got me hooked. I picked up a Wanhao Di3+, a CR-10, an Ender 3 and an Anycubic Photon since then and they are set up for different tasks. I would love to have the opportunity to try a large format resin printer at some point ... but I can give up anytime, I haven’t got a problem. :)

Curiosity as a lifestyle I like to know how to do a little of everything I always say that "there is nothing impossible if it is designed and implemented by a man I can do it too" space from 2D / 3D graphics to the restoration of motorcycles I do what I like it.

I am using a HIC Prusa I3, this is distinctive by its Z axis offset. I have modified it so that the carriage has a quick change plate suitable for changing tools, quickly converting from 1.75 bowden, to hold a DTI, or change to a paste extruder and print chocolate.

I did an electrical apprenticeship in the Royal Navy from 1979 to 1983, In 91 I completed my electronics Diploma, In 94 I got my first Degree in Digital Systems, then in 95 I got my second degree in Optical electronics. When I did my apprenticeship we had to do all sorts, including welding, milling, turning, even some foundry work and so with these skills I am competent in many engineering disciplines. In 2005 I invented "underwater mapping from the air using virtual transmitters and receivers", the idea was for shallow water from 1mm to a metre or so deep where the water may have, sand, clay, oil (on the surface) etc and may not accessable by boat (for sonar) or other methods. I was hoping to develop this at Plymouth University and gain a Phd, but allass funding could not be found.

Over the years I have worked for many companies in a wide variety of roles, this has all added to my experience and knowledge base, so when the time came I was happy to invent, play, and make new things for my own business.

Since 2010 I have had my own business "PrototypeMe" which is aimed at helping people get there idea's from an idea into a prototype. I realised how useful a 3D printer could be in making components for prototypes and invested in one. Seeing that they are not just useful as printers but as a 3 axis machine can do other tasks.

bio:
Howdy! I'm Steve Trambert. I'm a mechanical engineer working with FDM and full-color 3D printers. I tinker with 3D designs in my free time, and upload some of the successful ones here for others to download.

If you'd like to print one of my full-color models but do not have access to a 3D Systems or ZCorp color printer, you can order individual parts through a printing service. Here's one that should be able to accept the color VRML or ZPR files that I upload, although you could probably find more:
www.solidyte.com
or: http://www.3dhubs.com/boston/hubs/solidyte

You can also get my models printed in color "sandstone" from Shapeways. They'll take the VRML files I upload.

In some of my models, I will recommend printing the part on a ProJet 4500, which produces full-color plastic parts. If you want, you can try printing them on a color plaster machines instead, but beware that the model may be very fragile.
